<chapter><title>Installing Build Gear</title>

  <section><title> Supported GNU/Linux Distributions </title>

    <para>
      Build Gear is tested using Ubuntu 12.10 64-bit (Minimal). Installation on
      other GNU/Linux distributions is not supported.
    </para>

  </section>

  <section><title> Installing From Source </title>
    <para>
      Prepare Ubuntu for compilation and installation of Build Gear:
    </para>
<screen>$ sudo apt-get install build-essential libcurl4-gnutls-dev libncurses5-dev unzip</screen>

    <para>
      Build and install Build Gear:
    </para>
<screen>$ wget http://www.buildgear.org/release/buildgear-PACKAGE_VERSION.tar.xz
$ tar xf buildgear-PACKAGE_VERSION.tar.xz
$ cd buildgear-PACKAGE_VERSION
$ ./configure --prefix=$HOME/opt/buildgear
$ make
$ make install</screen>

    <para>
      Add Build Gear to your path, eg.:
    </para>
<screen>$ echo 'export PATH=$HOME/opt/buildgear/bin:$PATH' >> ~/.bashrc</screen>

    <para>
      Enable Build Gear bash auto completion, eg.:
    </para>
<screen>$ echo 'source $HOME/opt/buildgear/etc/bash_completion.d/buildgear-bash-completion.sh' >> ~/.bashrc</screen>
  </section>

  <section><title>Installing From Ubuntu PPA</title>
    <para>
      Installation via Ubuntu PPA is planned to be available in the future.
    </para>
  </section>

  <section><title>Optional VirtualBox Build Image</title>
    <para>
      A VirtualBox image with a preinstalled Ubuntu installation is available
      for those who do not have Ubuntu installed on their build computer.
    </para>

    <para>
      The Ubuntu VirtualBox image is available <ulink
      url="http://buildgear.org/release/Ubuntu-12.10-64bit-Minimal.vdi.tar.xz">here</ulink>.
    </para>

    <para>
      Simply extract and install the VDI disk image in a new Virtualbox
      session. Remember to configure the number of system CPUs according to the
      CPU count available in your system.  Also be generous when configuring
      available system memory. It is recommended to use a bridged network
      adapter to make it easy to connect to the virtual machine via ssh.
    </para>

    <para>
      The default username/password = ubuntu/ubuntu
    </para>

    <para>
      If needed you can do some Ubuntu reconfiguration as described below.
    </para>

    <para>
      Reconfigure keyboard language:
    </para>
<screen>$ sudo dpkg-reconfigure keyboard-configuration</screen>

    <para>
      Reconfigure time zone
    </para>
<screen>$ sudo dpkg-reconfigure tzdata</screen>

    <para>
      In case you run into boot delay due to network timeout you might need to do:
    </para>
<screen>$ sudo rm /etc/udev/rules.d/70-persistent-net.rules</screen>

  </section>
</chapter>
